Once your local development environment is set up, you'll need to clone 2 GitHub repositories to your project.

1) experience-builder-widget-themes


This repository is for the custom widgets and themes.


Use git clone https://github.com/People-Places-Solutions/experience-builder-widgets-themes.git custom-widgets-themes to clone the repo into the client directory.

2) experience-builder-apps


This repository is for containing the app configuration directories at the root level.


Use git clone https://github.com/People-Places-Solutions/experience-builder-apps.git apps to clone the repo into the ./server/public directory


*If an ./server/apps/ directory exists, you must rename it to something other than "apps", or remove it.
Getting Started
App Deployment

Custom Widget Hosting

1) Download

Download the experience to your machine and unzip the folder.

2) GitHub

Create a new GitHub repository and add the unzipped folder contents to the repository either from the GitHub UI or your IDE.

3) GitHub Pages

In your new GitHub repository Settings tab go to Pages and under the Build and deployment section select main for the Branch and click Save.

1) Static Web App

Go to Azure Portal and create a new Static Web App resource.

2A) GitHub

Under Deployment details select GitHub and continue with the rest of the steps.

2B) Azure DevOps

Under Deployment details select Azure DevOps and continue with the rest of the steps.

3) View Static App

Once the resource is created, you should be able to view it at https://[name].azurestaticapps.net

1) Compile the widget

In your development environment, run npm run build:prod under the client directory. Once you do that, the compiled widget show up in the client/dist-prod/widgets directory.

2) Add to GitHub

In the geospatial-developer-platform repo copy the widget folder from the client/dist-prod/widgets directory into the appropriate version folder under exb_widgets. You can find the widget version in the manifest.json.

3) Log the widget

Log the widget details here to add it to the widget library.
